    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <h3>Is Claude Code better than Cursor?</h3>
    <p>Claude Code is better for developers who need deep codebase analysis, large-scale refactoring, and autonomous agentic workflows thanks to its 200K-token context window and terminal-based AI agent. Cursor is better for developers who want a polished visual IDE with fast inline completions, multi-file Composer editing, and real-time codebase indexing. Neither is universally better — it depends on whether you prioritize terminal-based autonomous AI or an integrated AI-native IDE.</p>
    <h3>Is Cursor better than Claude Code for beginners?</h3>
    <p>Yes, Cursor is generally better for beginners. It provides a familiar VS Code-based visual IDE with inline suggestions, an intuitive chat panel, and natural language editing through Composer. Claude Code runs as a terminal CLI tool and requires comfort with command-line workflows, which can be intimidating for new developers. Beginners usually get productive faster in Cursor's visual environment.</p>
    <h3>Which AI coding assistant is better in 2026?</h3>
    <p>In 2026, choose Claude Code if you work on large codebases, need autonomous multi-step AI agents, and prefer terminal workflows. Choose Cursor if you want the most polished AI-native IDE with the fastest autocomplete and a visual editing experience. Both are top-tier AI coding assistants — the right choice depends on your workflow style and whether you favor terminal-based reasoning or visual IDE integration.</p>
    <h3>Can Claude Code replace Cursor?</h3>
    <p>Yes, Claude Code can replace Cursor for developers who prefer terminal-based workflows and need autonomous AI agents for large-scale refactoring and debugging. Claude Code works alongside any editor, so you can keep VS Code or JetBrains while using Claude Code for heavy lifting. However, developers who rely on Cursor's inline Tab autocomplete, visual Composer, and real-time codebase chat may find Claude Code lacks the integrated IDE experience they depend on.</p>
